<seg id="1042">If a picture is rendered with only one beam per pixel, various errors may arise. these images often have a Moir pattern or step-effects in curves and lines, and sometimes details are not displayed if they are smaller than a pixel in the representation. this effect is called Aliasing.</seg>
<seg id="1043">& Povray; uses a technique called anti-aliasing to reduce the impact of this error. generally pictures with this quality look better.</seg>
<seg id="1044">When you switch anti-aliasing, calculates and connects & Povray; more than one beam per pixel. this technique is called super-sampling.</seg>
<seg id="1045">& Povray; supports two methods of super-sampling. as standard is an adaptive, non-recursive method; adaptive because the super-sampling involves the adjacent pixels. the second method is adaptive-recursively; recursively because each pixel is split again and again and adaptively because the recursion depth depends on the calculated color values.</seg>
<seg id="1046">If you choose the first method, POV-Ray follows a ray per pixel. if the difference between the color values exceeds the given threshold, then both pixels are calculated by tracking a certain additional number of pixels with super-sampling. if you set the depth value to 4, a grid of 4x4 additional points will be calculated, with a depth value of 5 then 5x5 (25) additional rays each pixel.</seg>
<seg id="1047">The difference between two pixels is calculated as follows: r 1, g 1 and b 1 are the values for red, green and blue of the first pixel, r 2, g 2 and b 2 are the values for red, green and blue of the second pixel. the difference is:</seg>
<seg id="1048">Diff = abs (r 1 -r 2) + abs (g 1 -g 2) + abs (b 1 -b 2)</seg>
<seg id="1049">The recursive method starts with 4 rays each pixel. if the difference between the values exceeds the given threshold, then the pixels are divided into 4 sub-pixels, which are followed individually and can be checked for further subdivision. the maximum depth of recursion allows you to set the depth value.</seg>
